    "#### Sub-Problems Identified (5W Framework)\n",
    " \n",
    "| # | Sub-Problem | Who | What | Why |\n",
    "|---|---|---|---|---|\n",
    "| SP1 | **Transport-Driven Segments** | Respondents relying on private vehicles and frequent air travel | Cluster by transport mode, vehicle distance, and flight frequency | Strongest emission correlate (r = 0.59); ~1,100 kg CO₂ gap between private-vehicle users and walkers/cyclists |\n",
    "| SP2 | **Consumption & Waste Segments** | Respondents with high clothing purchases, large/frequent waste bags, low recycling | Cluster by consumption and waste features independent of transport | Moderate correlations (r = 0.20 clothes, r = 0.16 waste); often missed by transport-focused policies |\n",
    "| SP3 | **Energy & Housing Segments** | Respondents using coal/wood heating vs. electricity | Cluster by household energy behaviours | ~400 kg CO₂ gap between coal and electricity users |\n",
    "| SP4 | **Diet & Food Segments** | Respondents grouped by diet type and grocery spending | Cluster by diet and food features | Smallest gap (~175 kg CO₂); unlikely to define clusters alone |\n",
    "| SP5 | **Low-Emission Exemplars** | Bottom-quartile emitters (below ~1,538 kg CO₂) | Identify and profile \"green exemplar\" clusters | Enables positive-deviance campaigns with achievable behaviour bundles |\n",
    "| SP6 | **Outlier & Extreme Profiles** | Upper-tail emitters (above ~5,000 kg CO₂) | Detect outliers via DBSCAN | Small population but disproportionate emissions; may need regulatory interventions |"
   ]
